### Using FORCE level 2 results as an input

The process graph for FORCE TSA built in the same way as the level 2 process graph is built.
The main input for FORCE TSA is the STAC catalog (or item) from the level 2 processing.

We can access the catalog from the level 2 job as described in [level 2 processing article](level2.qmd#Accessing results).

We can re-use a job that has run previously using the job ID (which you can find out through the web interface or using) [`list_jobs`](https://open-eo.github.io/openeo-python-client/api.html#openeo.rest.connection.Connection.list_jobs)

```{.python}
jobs = connection.list_jobs() # extract job id of your level 2 job
l2_job = connection.job("<job-id>")
```



### TSA Parameters

Some parameters can be set a-priori or from prior knowledge of our level 2 processing parameters

::: {#ca44bab5 .cell execution_count=13}
``` {.python .cell-code}
temporal_extent=["2026-02-01", "2026-02-20"]
```
:::


For other parameters, we may want to inspect the metadata of the level 2 processing.
For example, we can extract the tiles from the asset names of the STAC item describing the level 2 datacube. 

::: {#b2255307 .cell execution_count=14}
``` {.python .cell-code}
# See the level 2 article for the definition of this function
l2_catalog_url = extract_catalog_url_from_job_logs(l2_job.logs())
l2_catalog = pystac.Catalog.from_file(l2_catalog_url)
l2_item = next(l2_catalog.get_items()) # there is just one item
l2_item
```

